The upward context scan in Wrappin is still useful, but it was too permissive: if the first selected row was plain text and the row above was a comment/list marker, Wrappin would inherit that schema unconditionally. In real code this meant a selected branch line below `// BRANCH` could be reflowed as repeated `//` comment lines. The fix is intentionally narrow. We keep inherited schema for genuine continuation rows, but refuse inheritance when the first selected row looks code-like (closing delimiters, braces/semicolons, or common operator sequences).

That keeps the existing list-continuation feature alive for prose while blocking the most damaging misclassification path. The adjacent spec uses the reported C-like branch example shape so future refactors cannot regress back into commenting out code just because a nearby marker exists.

